Aim:
To write a C++ program that demonstrates unary operator overloading using a class.

Algorithm:
Start the program.
Create a class with an integer data member.
Define a constructor to initialize the value.
Overload unary operator ++ using a member function.
Create an object and apply the overloaded operator.
Display results.
End the program.

Program:
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Number {
    int x;
public:
    Number(int a) {
        x = a;
    }

    void operator++() {      // Unary operator overloading
        x = x + 1;
    }

    void display() {
        cout << "Value: " << x << endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    Number n(5);
    cout << "Before Overloading:" << endl;
    n.display();

    ++n;   // calling unary operator overload

    cout << "After Overloading (++):" << endl;
    n.display();

    return 0;
}

Output:
Before Overloading:
Value: 5
After Overloading (++):
Value: 6

Result:
Unary operator overloading was successfully implemented using a class.


Start the program.
